english:
  title: Reflections on the Sea from Gyeyang
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    From the tower of Manwol Temple, I first gazed upon the sea. Great ships at the center of the waves appeared no larger than ducks swimming, while smaller boats seemed like men half-submerged with only their heads visible above water. Departing sails resembled men walking in tall hats. The multitude of mountains and islands lay distant and mysterious—some towering, some bare, some crouching, some prone, some with ridges exposed, some crowned like topknots, some hollowed through like caves, some rounded like parasol handles.

    A monk came to point them out, naming the islands with his finger: "There lies Purple Swallow Island, High Crane Island, Qilin Island." And the mountains: "There stands the Crane Ridge of the capital, there the guardian peak of Ascended Heaven Prefecture, Dragon Mountain, the vista from Inzhou, the view toward Tongiin." He recited them all as easily as pointing at his palm. That day I rejoiced greatly, drank with my companions in celebration, and returned home intoxicated.

    Days later, I visited Myeongwol Temple and enjoyed similar pleasures, though many mountains obscured the view—not as open and vast as Manwol. Days after that, I rode northward along the slopes and eastward beside the sea, observing the surge of tides and the shifting mirages that dance upon the waters. Sometimes on horseback, sometimes on foot, I wandered until weariness compelled my return, my companions carrying wine throughout our expedition.

    Ah, but this water is the same water as before, and this heart is the same heart. Yet what I once despised to look upon, I now delight in observing. Is this not because of a petty office gained? My heart is my own, yet I cannot master it. So easily does it shift with circumstance. Can I hope to regard life and death as one, gain and loss as equal? I record this as a warning to my future self.
  footnotes:
    - 'Manwol Temple (萬日寺): Lee Kyubo is appointed to govern Gyeyang and initially finds the surrounding waters oppressive; after two years, upon receiving promotion and preparing to return to the capital, his perception transforms completely.'
    - The monk's identification of islands and mountains refers to specific landmarks visible from Gyeyang's coast, connecting the local geography to the broader Korean landscape.
    - The philosophical conclusion reflects Buddhist and Daoist thought on the impermanence of perception and the danger of attachment to circumstantial emotions.
